  "Idea": "This paper introduces Reciprocal Style Translation with Sparse Latent Alignment (RST-SLA), a novel framework for enhancing model stability during formal-to-informal domain transitions by reframing auxiliary learning as a bidirectional style translation task with structural regularization. Rather than treating formal and informal language as distinct domains requiring protection against interference, RST-SLA posits that their semantic overlap can be exploited through mutual reconstruction: the model learns to translate any utterance into both its formal and informal counterparts, using this duality to anchor shared representations. At the heart of the framework is a dual-generator architecture—each specializing in one direction of style transfer (formal→informal and informal→formal)—that share a common encoder but maintain separate lightweight decoders. These generators are activated adaptively via a meta-controller similar to DATS-RS, but now guided by *symmetry loss*: the discrepancy between reconstructions when translating forward and back (e.g., formal → informal → formal). High symmetry loss indicates representational drift and triggers increased weighting of the corresponding style translation task. Crucially, we introduce a Sparse Cross-Style Attention Module (SCSAM) that identifies and preserves invariant semantic units—such as intent markers, slot entities, or discourse roles—by enforcing sparse alignment between attention heads across the two stylistic representations. This module computes an associative structure graph over key tokens and aligns edges only when they reflect stable, high-confidence mappings (e.g., 'I wanna book a flight' ↔ 'I would like to reserve a flight'). The SCSAM operates similarly to the sparse associative alignment in Paper 3 but is applied across stylistic variants rather than temporal segments, creating a causality-inspired bridge between forms. Additionally, we incorporate a memory-augmented buffer storing prototype pairs (matched formal-informal utterances) sampled from high-symmetry regions, which are replayed during low-drift phases to reinforce consistency. This approach transforms auxiliary tasks from passive stabilizers into active co-trainers: improving style translation inherently strengthens both formal and informal understanding. The potential impact extends beyond dialogue systems to any application involving mixed-register user input, such as clinical note summarization (from doctor-patient chat), legal assistance bots, or educational tools. Models trained with RST-SLA are expected to exhibit superior robustness, maintaining >90% Joint Goal Accuracy on formal benchmarks post-transition while achieving state-of-the-art performance on informal intent detection, all with minimal auxiliary overhead due to shared computation.",
  "Title": "Reciprocal Style Translation with Sparse Latent Alignment for Stable Formal-Informal Domain Adaptation",
  "Experiment": "The experimental design consists of four stages. First, we curate a parallel corpus by aligning formal and informal utterances using heuristic matching (e.g., paraphrase detection via SBERT) on datasets like MultiWOZ (formal) and ConvAI2 or Twitter Dialog (informal), augmented with synthetic pairs generated via controlled style transfer models. Second, we implement the RST-SLA framework using a base encoder (e.g., DeBERTa-v3) with two lightweight decoders (one per style). The meta-controller—an LSTM network—monitors rolling symmetry loss, KL divergence between cross-style attention maps, and feature sparsity to determine when to activate each generator. The SCSAM is implemented via a differentiable sparse attention mechanism that selects top-k inter-style token alignments based on cosine similarity and syntactic role overlap. Third, we evaluate against baselines: (1) standard fine-tuning, (2) fixed multi-task style transfer, (3) DATS-RS, and (4) replay + EWC. Primary metrics include symmetry preservation score (SPS = 1 - normalized forward-backward reconstruction loss), JGA retention on formal tasks, F1 on informal intent classification, and Catastrophic Forgetting Index. We also measure computational efficiency via FLOPs per auxiliary task invocation. Ideal outcomes include SPS > 0.85, <3% CFI, and adaptive activation peaking during mid-transition epochs. Ablation studies will assess contributions of SCSAM, symmetry loss, and memory replay. All code, aligned corpora, and probing tools will be released.",
  "Clarity": 9,
  "Feasibility": 8,
  "Novelty": 10
}```
