  "Experiment": "The experimental design involves three main stages. First, we establish a formal-to-informal transition pipeline using datasets like MultiWOZ (formal) and ConvAI2 or Twitter Dialog (informal). A base model (e.g., BERT or DeBERTa) is pre-trained on formal dialogue state tracking and then gradually exposed to informal conversations. Second, we implement the meta-controller using a lightweight LSTM that takes as input rolling statistics of representation drift: KL divergence between formal/informal attention maps, variance in hidden states across layers, and drop in performance on a held-out formal validation set. The controller outputs a probability distribution over auxiliary tasks (reconstruction, POS tagging, coreference, formality classification), sampled to determine which loss to include in each batch. Third, we compare DATS-RS against baselines: (1) no auxiliary tasks, (2) fixed multi-task learning, (3) replay-based methods, and (4) EWC. Evaluation metrics include Joint Goal Accuracy (JGA) on formal tasks post-transition, F1 on informal intent detection, and Catastrophic Forgetting Index (CFI = drop in formal performance). We also measure auxiliary task efficiency (gain per added computation). Ideal outcomes include <5% CFI, >85% JGA retention, and adaptive task usage peaking during high-drift epochs. Ablation studies will test individual components (e.g., removing the memory module). All code and probes will be released.",
